Prior to the past 3 years, I hadn't heard that phrase since early 80's when I was in *early* grade school. It just went the hell away for a while, then some genius tacked on a GHE to it (ghey), updated it for the new milennium, and I guess it's &quot;cool&quot; again to say it over and over....whatever. It pissed me off again when the use of that word that way reared it's head again- then I just remember the &quot;brilliant&quot; people in the sandbox who used it back when I was playing with GIJoes. Same mentality, and it'll be gone again and replaced with something equally as stupid. Just take it from the source and shrug it off, man. Not worth getting upset over anymore. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukloeviseq.showPublicProfile?language=EN>KloevisEQ</A> at: 8/1/02 6:37:04 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usyllestraefv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New Mod!</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/1/02 6:48 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: That is so str8!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> That surprises the heck out of me who lives here in the South. Most folks of color I know don't use it and take great offense in it still being used. The only ones I know who still use it are really old white people who think it's more to say than the N word.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
   Well, in theory anyways.  One of my friends at summer camp was from therabouts and used the word from time to time so I thought it was still in infrequent use.  I've only been to Alabama / Georgia once (for a family reunion).<br>
<br>
   I'm half-black (half-caucasian) and I've used it once myself (albeit on accident).  Prior to college, I referred to non-caucasians as &quot;minorities&quot;.  College was where I first heard the term &quot;persons of color&quot; and I thought it was a much better phrase.  I was then speaking about something in class, meant to use &quot;persons of color&quot;, and it came out of my mouth &quot;colored&quot;.  <br>
<br>
   It's all about knowledge &amp; intent.  If someone's aware that the wording of a phrase (ie: &quot;gay&quot;, &quot;indian giver&quot;, etc) is offensive, and intentionally keeps using it, they suck.  If someone hasn't thought about the wording enough to realize it's offensive, or wasn't using it intentionally, I'd have a hard time holding anything against them.<br>
<br>
- Syll<br>
